13:14.027 --> 13:16.129
‐ Dear Elisabeth Anne,

13:16.162 --> 13:18.097
enclosed is
an itemized statement

13:18.131 --> 13:20.433
explaining my sanctions
for this month.

13:20.466 --> 13:23.002
As you will see,
the deductions for the month

13:23.036 --> 13:25.938
exceed your allowance
of $9,000.

13:29.942 --> 13:32.078
[soft dramatic music]

13:32.111 --> 13:34.614
Leaving a balance due
from you to me

13:34.647 --> 13:37.417
of $1,315.32.

13:37.450 --> 13:41.754
Now, I know your first impulse
upon reading this letter

13:41.788 --> 13:43.623
will be a violent one.

13:43.656 --> 13:45.291
I would think twice about that.

13:45.325 --> 13:48.695
If you make any attack on me
or my property,

13:48.728 --> 13:51.364
you will never again
get a red cent out of me

13:51.397 --> 13:54.267
without a court order.

13:54.300 --> 13:57.503
Sincerely,
Daniel T. Broderick, III.

13:57.537 --> 14:01.007
♪ ♪

14:01.040 --> 14:03.009
‐ How will she pay her bills?

14:21.094 --> 14:21.627
‐ Guess I owe you another $250.

14:22.662 --> 14:23.730
‐ Get out of here now.

14:23.763 --> 14:26.265
‐ Or you'll be late
for the black stone ball?

14:26.299 --> 14:27.934
Uh‐oh!

14:27.967 --> 14:30.269
Better hurry up and go get
your shitty cape and top hat

14:30.303 --> 14:32.438
and take the whore to the party
I should be going to.

14:32.472 --> 14:34.107
‐ Just leave.
‐ No.

14:34.140 --> 14:36.275
‐ I'll call the cops.
‐ Oh, I know you will.

14:36.309 --> 14:38.745
‐ They'll arrest you, Bets.
‐ You'll have me arrested!

14:38.778 --> 14:42.148
‐ You'll go to jail this time!
‐ You'll have me sent to jail!

14:42.181 --> 14:43.649
No!

14:46.018 --> 14:48.988
[tense music]

14:49.021 --> 14:52.658
♪ ♪

14:52.692 --> 14:55.361
And they did a warrant check
on me to see if I had

14:55.395 --> 14:58.364
a criminal history,
which obviously I didn't.

14:58.398 --> 14:59.766
‐ Betty...

14:59.799 --> 15:01.834
‐ Though I guess now I do.

15:01.868 --> 15:03.669
[exhales sharply]

15:03.703 --> 15:07.039
So then I waited
and they brought me

15:07.073 --> 15:10.610
a bologna sandwich
that smelled like a foot,

15:10.643 --> 15:14.781
and then they let me go
on my own recognizance.

15:14.814 --> 15:18.684
What is so wrong with asking
how I'm supposed to live

15:18.718 --> 15:19.619
for a month with no money?

15:19.652 --> 15:22.622
‐ So what does Dan say
you owe him?

15:24.157 --> 15:25.925
‐ $1,300.

15:25.958 --> 15:29.562
‐ So he deducted your entire
support check plus $1,300?

15:29.595 --> 15:31.798
[dramatic music]

15:31.831 --> 15:33.966
I'm writing you a check.
‐ Oh, no.

15:34.000 --> 15:35.902
‐ I can do $6,500.

15:37.570 --> 15:39.906
Yes, I am.

15:39.939 --> 15:41.908
[chuckles]

15:41.941 --> 15:43.676
[pen scribbling]

15:43.709 --> 15:46.479
[pensive music]

15:46.512 --> 15:53.619
♪ ♪

16:11.003 --> 16:13.239
‐ Shaking in my bed.

16:13.272 --> 16:15.608
Feels like an earthquake.

16:15.641 --> 16:17.176
Miserable.
Miserable.

16:17.210 --> 16:19.579
Miserable, miserable bastard.

16:19.612 --> 16:21.447
You want everything your way.

16:21.481 --> 16:23.716
You have no sense
of right, wrong,

16:23.749 --> 16:27.453
true, false,
indecent, immoral.

16:27.487 --> 16:29.589
God will pay you back for it.

16:29.622 --> 16:35.394
♪ ♪

16:35.428 --> 16:37.563
‐ August 7th, 1986.

16:37.597 --> 16:39.565
Ronald P. Ollen
appointed by the court

16:39.599 --> 16:44.003
to mediate the matter
of Broderick versus Broderick.

16:44.036 --> 16:46.205
Also present,
Elisabeth Broderick.

16:46.239 --> 16:48.608
Will you be represented
by counsel?

16:48.641 --> 16:50.943
‐ I'm not‐‐

16:50.977 --> 16:53.479
I‐‐I've had some trouble there.

16:53.513 --> 16:56.449
Shouldn't we wait for Dan?

16:56.482 --> 16:59.151
‐ Uh, Mr. Broderick
won't be joining us.

16:59.185 --> 17:01.654
It's customary to meet
with both parties separately

17:01.687 --> 17:05.024
to determine whether there is a
basis for conflict resolution.

17:07.226 --> 17:09.028
‐ And what if there isn't?

17:09.061 --> 17:11.397
‐ Mediation is only
as successful

17:11.430 --> 17:13.399
as the parties want it to be.

17:13.432 --> 17:15.001
Did you prepare your statement?

17:22.208 --> 17:23.809
‐ Oh, I didn't‐‐
‐ Oh.

17:23.843 --> 17:25.645
‐ I thought I was going
to be reading it aloud

17:25.678 --> 17:28.581
to the room.

17:28.614 --> 17:31.651
‐ Well, you're welcome to
read it aloud into the record.

17:43.529 --> 17:45.064
‐ Ready?

17:48.100 --> 17:52.271
Let me first say how nervous
and overwhelmed I am.

17:52.305 --> 17:54.674
My entire life‐‐
past, present, and future‐‐

17:54.707 --> 17:56.242
is on the table.

17:56.275 --> 17:59.512
Your past, present, and future
are right on track.

17:59.545 --> 18:01.314
The children and I
have been victimized

18:01.347 --> 18:03.516
by the one person who
was supposed to protect us

18:03.549 --> 18:05.952
from harm,
not cause it.

18:05.985 --> 18:07.954
When I am assured
of financial security,

18:07.987 --> 18:09.956
I will begin
to discuss custody.

18:09.989 --> 18:12.124
For now I am too enraged
by your actions

18:12.158 --> 18:15.127
to accept any responsibility
for our children

18:15.161 --> 18:17.530
because I don't know how
to raise secure,

18:17.563 --> 18:20.800
happy, healthy children with
a sense of right and wrong

18:20.833 --> 18:23.736
when you are living proof
that none of my values

18:23.769 --> 18:25.404
are worth a damn.

18:25.438 --> 18:28.407
[tense music]

18:28.441 --> 18:35.047
♪ ♪

18:35.081 --> 18:38.384
Did Mr. Broderick prepare
a position statement?

18:38.417 --> 18:39.585
Can I hear it?

18:39.619 --> 18:42.822
‐ Mr. Broderick has opted not
to make a position statement

18:42.855 --> 18:45.625
as is his right under the law.

18:46.759 --> 18:48.628
‐ [scoffs]

18:48.661 --> 18:51.063
[indistinct chatter]

18:51.097 --> 18:52.498
‐ Hey.

18:52.531 --> 18:54.200
You see who's here?
Lou Clapper.

18:54.233 --> 18:56.369
‐ Oh, that hammer toe.

18:56.402 --> 18:58.671
Every time I hear his voice,
my nose starts bleeding.

18:58.704 --> 19:00.406
[all laughing]

19:00.439 --> 19:02.375
‐ Can I talk to you a minute?
‐ Mm, sure.

19:02.408 --> 19:05.044
[lounge music playing]

19:05.077 --> 19:09.382
♪ ♪

19:09.415 --> 19:11.150
‐ Um...
[clears throat]

19:11.183 --> 19:14.720
Betty told me about the fines
and sanctions

19:14.754 --> 19:17.523
and the money she owes you now,

19:17.556 --> 19:21.894
and about jail.

19:21.927 --> 19:25.264
Dan, don't you think
this is all...

19:28.401 --> 19:31.604
Getting out of hand?

19:31.637 --> 19:34.874
‐ I think you have
a warped perception

19:34.907 --> 19:37.576
of the details of my life,
which is understandable.

19:37.610 --> 19:41.714
It's not as understandable why
you need to involve yourself

19:41.747 --> 19:43.949
and spread those perceptions
as fact.

19:43.983 --> 19:46.285
‐ Is this thing on?
Can anyone hear me?

19:46.318 --> 19:48.821
‐ Maybe focus more
on your own life, Ev,

19:48.854 --> 19:51.290
instead of titillating yourself

19:51.323 --> 19:54.293
and other people with stories
about mine.

19:54.326 --> 19:55.661
Excuse us.

19:55.695 --> 19:57.463
‐ Anybody see him?

19:57.496 --> 19:59.799
[applause]

19:59.832 --> 20:02.435
‐ You're unbelievable.
‐ I warned you.

20:02.468 --> 20:06.038
‐ Of the San Diego County
Bar Association,

20:06.072 --> 20:08.908
in the year of our Lord 1987,

20:08.941 --> 20:11.510
Daniel T. Broderick, III.

20:11.544 --> 20:13.045
[cheers and applause]

20:20.619 --> 20:20.920
[dramatic music]

20:23.456 --> 20:27.059
♪ ♪

20:27.093 --> 20:28.894
‐ You'll like Hilary.
She's your style.

20:28.928 --> 20:30.229
‐ Thanks, Evelyn.

20:30.262 --> 20:33.132
‐ But don't say
Richard referred you.

20:33.165 --> 20:34.934
You can tell her once
she's your lawyer,

20:34.967 --> 20:36.102
but until then,

20:36.135 --> 20:40.005
just maybe don't bring
Richard's name into it.

20:40.039 --> 20:42.007
‐ Oh, yeah, of course.
I won't.

20:42.041 --> 20:44.610
Thank you and Richard so much.

20:44.643 --> 20:46.612
‐ Call her today.

20:46.645 --> 20:48.948
♪ ♪

20:48.981 --> 20:50.516
[door opening]

20:53.953 --> 20:57.156
‐ Betty, I'm Hilary Clark.

20:58.924 --> 21:00.726
That's a gorgeous color on you.

21:00.760 --> 21:03.529
‐ Thank you.

21:03.562 --> 21:07.566
I wanna ask for maybe a quarter
of what he makes per month.

21:07.600 --> 21:09.602
I say maybe because
however much I'm guessing,

21:09.635 --> 21:11.604
I'm pretty sure he makes more.

21:11.637 --> 21:13.405
‐ What do you think
a quarter is?

21:13.439 --> 21:15.441
‐ 28.5.

21:15.474 --> 21:17.143
My expenses are high,

21:17.176 --> 21:18.978
but they're consistent
with the living standard

21:19.011 --> 21:21.413
I earned during my marriage
to Dan.

21:21.447 --> 21:24.583
The point is fairness,
percentages.

21:24.617 --> 21:26.886
Half of everything
Dan Broderick has is mine.

21:26.919 --> 21:28.954
I'm not asking for half.

21:28.988 --> 21:30.990
But why should
my lifestyle decline

21:31.023 --> 21:33.759
when he wouldn't have
his lifestyle without me?

21:33.793 --> 21:35.728
‐ And what about custody?

21:35.761 --> 21:37.596
‐ I want that, too.
‐ Okay.

21:37.630 --> 21:40.166
So‐‐
‐ But not without a settlement.

21:40.199 --> 21:42.368
Not without being able
to take care of them

21:42.401 --> 21:43.736
in a way that I had planned.

21:43.769 --> 21:46.372
‐ I hear what you're saying.

21:46.405 --> 21:49.475
But from a strategic
standpoint,

21:49.508 --> 21:51.243
it'll be easier
to convince a judge

21:51.277 --> 21:54.580
to grant a settlement
if you have custody.

21:54.613 --> 21:57.449
You've got a court mandated
psych eval pending anyway

21:57.483 --> 21:58.517
tied to visitation.

21:58.551 --> 22:01.487
Let's get that on our side
while I start digging

22:01.520 --> 22:02.588
into Dan's financials.

22:02.621 --> 22:05.591
That sound fair?

22:05.624 --> 22:09.094
Can you stop calling
and going to his house?

22:12.498 --> 22:14.633
Can you stay away
from the kids?

22:14.667 --> 22:17.236
For the time being.

22:18.704 --> 22:20.539
Can you return my phone calls?

22:20.573 --> 22:22.174
‐ [laughs softly]

22:23.309 --> 22:30.349
♪ ♪

22:32.251 --> 22:35.187
‐ This is family court
calendar number one,

22:35.221 --> 22:36.889
Broderick versus Broderick.

22:36.922 --> 22:38.858
Are we ready to proceed?

22:38.891 --> 22:40.893
‐ Uh, there is one thing
we'd like to bring

22:40.926 --> 22:41.894
to the court's attention,
Your Honor.

22:41.927 --> 22:42.928
As the court knows,

22:42.962 --> 22:44.830
there have been numerous orders
to show cause

22:44.864 --> 22:46.232
filed on this matter,

22:46.265 --> 22:47.533
one of which prohibits
Mrs. Broderick

22:47.566 --> 22:49.134
from harassing Mr. Broderick
by phone.

22:49.168 --> 22:50.903
‐ Yes, I read the file,
Mr. Mills.

22:50.936 --> 22:52.504
‐ At 9:30 p. m.
on Tuesday the 5th,

22:52.538 --> 22:54.573
Mrs. Broderick phoned
Mr. Broderick's home.

22:54.607 --> 22:56.575
When Mr. Broderick
answered the phone,

22:56.609 --> 22:58.711
Mrs. Broderick said,
"Oh, dickhead,"

22:58.744 --> 22:59.578
and then hung up.

22:59.612 --> 23:01.714
‐ Actually, I'm glad
you brought this up,

23:01.747 --> 23:05.384
and I'm speaking to you
as well, Mr. Broderick.

23:05.417 --> 23:07.319
Going forward,

23:07.353 --> 23:11.090
you will not use this court
to litigate minor infractions.

23:11.123 --> 23:13.459
We will proceed
in an efficient manner

23:13.492 --> 23:14.994
and I will not tolerate
any attempt

23:15.027 --> 23:16.495
to waste my time with garbage.

23:16.528 --> 23:17.997
Are we clear, gentlemen?

23:18.030 --> 23:20.099
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ Yes, Your Honor.

23:20.132 --> 23:21.800
‐ Now, Ms. Clark.
[clears throat]

23:21.834 --> 23:24.103
You're requesting
to move forward immediately

23:24.136 --> 23:26.238
with your client's
psych evaluation

23:26.272 --> 23:28.073
with respects to visitation?

23:28.107 --> 23:29.508
‐ Yes, Your Honor.
‐ Very good.

23:29.541 --> 23:34.613
I'll appoint Dr. Margot Hayes
and we can set this matter down

23:34.647 --> 23:37.449
for delivery of her report
in, say, three weeks.

23:37.483 --> 23:39.919
Anything else?
‐ Thank you, Your Honor.

23:39.952 --> 23:40.853
‐ No, sir.

23:40.886 --> 23:42.354
‐ Get a date from my clerk

23:42.388 --> 23:45.758
and I'll see you
all back here then.

23:45.791 --> 23:47.726
[tender music]

23:47.760 --> 23:49.495
‐ [whispering]
The front.

23:51.163 --> 23:53.632
[normal voice]
Hi, hi!

23:53.666 --> 23:55.501
Sweetie, close the door.

23:55.534 --> 23:57.102
♪ ♪

23:57.136 --> 23:59.338
What's he doing?
‐ He's on a conference call.

23:59.371 --> 24:00.306
‐ Great.

24:00.339 --> 24:01.307
We'll be done before
he even knows you're gone.

24:01.340 --> 24:04.610
Now, is the paper on
Andrew Johnson as President

24:04.643 --> 24:07.146
specifically,
or on reconstruction?

24:07.179 --> 24:08.981
‐ Him as President.

24:09.014 --> 24:11.150
‐ That is what I thought.

24:11.183 --> 24:14.420
♪ ♪

24:14.453 --> 24:15.821
Oh, and...

24:15.854 --> 24:18.257
‐ [gasps]
Yes!

24:18.290 --> 24:21.427
[laughter]

24:22.628 --> 24:25.164
‐ Can you tell me how
Mr. Broderick

24:25.197 --> 24:27.032
got custody of the children?

24:27.066 --> 24:31.470
‐ Well, I was living without
a support agreement

24:31.503 --> 24:33.505
in a big huge house
that he had told me to buy,

24:33.539 --> 24:36.308
and all of a sudden,
it was infested with rats.

24:36.342 --> 24:38.744
So I took my children
and I dropped them off at Dan's

24:38.777 --> 24:41.814
and left them there, and...

24:41.847 --> 24:43.115
you know what
that son of a bitch did?

24:43.148 --> 24:45.084
‐ No.

24:45.117 --> 24:46.952
‐ He kept them.
‐ Okay.

24:46.986 --> 24:49.154
‐ I don't want you
to take notes.

24:49.188 --> 24:51.256
‐ Okay.

24:52.224 --> 24:54.526
Well‐‐
[clears throat]

24:54.560 --> 24:56.228
As an attorney,

24:56.261 --> 24:58.797
Mr. Broderick, uh,

24:58.831 --> 25:01.266
must work, you know,

25:01.300 --> 25:03.969
very difficult hours,
so it seems to me

25:04.003 --> 25:06.338
that since you were
the primary parent

25:06.372 --> 25:08.040
that we should be able

25:08.073 --> 25:10.776
to work out
something reasonable.

25:10.809 --> 25:13.212
Depending on what
the children tell me,

25:13.245 --> 25:17.549
I'm sure they can probably
come back and live with you

25:17.583 --> 25:20.919
since Mr. Broderick, uh,
wasn't awarded custody

25:20.953 --> 25:25.657
as part of an actual contested
litigation in court.

25:25.691 --> 25:29.695
♪ ♪

25:29.728 --> 25:33.232
‐ I'm not gonna be
a single parent of four kids.

25:33.265 --> 25:35.267
He'll die first.

25:37.269 --> 25:40.339
‐ [clears throat]
Are you threatening him?

25:40.372 --> 25:43.308
‐ I threaten him all the time.

25:50.082 --> 25:50.616
‐ Can't sleep.
Back pain.

25:51.483 --> 25:54.119
Grinding my teeth.
Headaches.

25:54.153 --> 25:56.321
Depressed.
Anxiety.

25:56.355 --> 25:58.757
Called Hilary at 1:00 a. m.

25:58.791 --> 26:00.793
Feeling out of control.
Still no money.

26:00.826 --> 26:03.095
Do I have ulcers?

26:03.128 --> 26:05.597
Missed Caseys' party,
Ireland Fund party,

26:05.631 --> 26:08.333
Milliken party,
Armstrong family party.

26:08.367 --> 26:10.803
Girls don't come or call.

26:10.836 --> 26:13.238
Think house has termites.
Roof leaking.

26:13.272 --> 26:15.140
Trapped by fear.

26:15.174 --> 26:16.842
Solitary confinement,

26:16.875 --> 26:19.445
the cruelest punishment
short of the electric chair.

26:19.478 --> 26:22.448
[tense music]

26:22.481 --> 26:24.950
The court order doesn't say
he has to pay by the first

26:24.983 --> 26:26.985
so he just sends it whenever
he feels like it.

26:27.019 --> 26:28.787
Sometimes not even
by the end of the month,

26:28.821 --> 26:31.623
so then my bills are backed up

26:31.657 --> 26:34.726
and paying them late
costs more.

26:34.760 --> 26:36.395
I tried looking for a job
in child care

26:36.428 --> 26:39.465
like you suggested
and found something.

26:39.498 --> 26:42.134
They were looking for a nanny
with teaching experience‐‐

26:42.167 --> 26:44.203
a six‐year old
and four‐year‐old twins‐‐

26:44.236 --> 26:45.871
and I almost applied,
but then I thought,

26:45.904 --> 26:48.173
"How am I gonna explain why
I don't have my own kids?"

26:50.843 --> 26:54.379
I didn't even get to see Ryan
on his birthday.

26:54.413 --> 26:58.383
‐ I'm sorry.
This is so hard.

26:58.417 --> 26:59.351
‐ Thank you.

26:59.384 --> 27:01.753
‐ But can I give you
some good news?

27:01.787 --> 27:04.323
Our request for you to have
the boys Easter weekend

27:04.356 --> 27:06.758
was approved.
‐ Really?

27:06.792 --> 27:08.627
‐ Whatever channels
it went through,

27:08.660 --> 27:11.330
whoever had to sign off,
they did.

27:11.363 --> 27:12.998
And I know it doesn't help
with any

27:13.031 --> 27:15.100
of what you were just saying‐‐
‐ No, it does.

27:18.937 --> 27:20.539
Really does.

27:22.341 --> 27:25.077
[phone ringing]

27:28.881 --> 27:30.716
Hello?
‐ Mrs. Broderick?

27:30.749 --> 27:33.051
It's Mrs. Walsh,
Anthony's homeroom teacher.

27:33.085 --> 27:34.219
‐ What's the matter?
Is everything okay?

27:34.253 --> 27:36.221
‐ He's feeling pretty sick.
He should be at home,

27:36.255 --> 27:40.559
but I haven't been able
to track down Mr. Broderick.

27:40.592 --> 27:44.229
I had to bring him to the nurse
right after morning assembly.

27:44.263 --> 27:48.033
Usually I can eventually
at least reach the housekeeper.

27:48.066 --> 27:49.168
I don't know what's
going on today.

27:49.201 --> 27:51.570
‐ Uh, is it the housekeeper's
job to give you a bath,

27:51.603 --> 27:53.906
usually?

27:53.939 --> 27:59.545
‐ Anthony's just had
a lot of colds this winter.

27:59.578 --> 28:01.547
Oh, and incidentally,

28:01.580 --> 28:04.716
we think we finally know
who patient zero was.

28:04.750 --> 28:06.385
‐ For his cold?

28:06.418 --> 28:08.954
‐ No, the lice.
Adair Keller.

28:08.987 --> 28:10.489
Her mother thinks she got it

28:10.522 --> 28:12.257
from the headrest
in a movie theater.

28:12.291 --> 28:13.859
‐ My son had lice?

28:15.360 --> 28:17.963
‐ I‐‐I didn't know
you didn't know.

28:17.996 --> 28:20.032
‐ Or you didn't think I cared.

28:21.500 --> 28:23.435
‐ Mrs. Broderick,

28:23.468 --> 28:25.637
I've seen you with your kids.

28:25.671 --> 28:27.206
I could never think
you didn't care.

28:29.041 --> 28:31.777
[Clarence Carter's
"Soul Deep"]

28:31.810 --> 28:34.546
‐ Can you walk?

28:34.580 --> 28:36.548
‐ Can you park first in line?

28:36.582 --> 28:39.284
‐ Absolutely.
I will be first in line.

28:39.318 --> 28:40.352
‐ Can we plant jelly beans?

28:40.385 --> 28:43.088
‐ And a carrot cake
for the Easter bunny!

28:43.121 --> 28:45.691
‐ Can you pick us up early?
‐ [laughs]

